# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tidb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tidb/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:tidb/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] A **distributed SQL** database is a single relational database which replicates data across multiple servers.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases are strongly consistent and most support consistency across racks, data centers, and wide area networks including cloud availability zones and cloud geographic zones.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases typically use the Paxos or Raft algorithms to achieve consensus across multiple nodes.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Sometimes distributed SQL databases are referred to as NewSQL but NewSQL is a more inclusive term that includes databases that are not distributed databases.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Google's Spanner popularized the modern distributed SQL database concept.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Spanner uses atomic clocks with the Paxos algorithm to accomplish consensus with regards to state distributed between servers.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] In 2010, and earlier implementation, ClustrixDB (now MariaDB Xpand) moved from a hardware appliance to a Paxos-based software database and was later acquired by MariaDB and added to a SaaS cloud offering called SkySQL.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] In 2015, two Google engineers left the company to create Cockroach DB which achieves similar results using the Raft algorithm without atomic clocks or custom hardware.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Spanner is primarily used for transactional and time-series use cases.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] However, Google furthered this research with a follow on paper about Google F1 which it describes as a Hybrid transactional/analytical processing database built on Spanner.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Following the CAP Theorem, distributed SQL databases are "CP" or consistent and partition-tolerant.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Algorithmically they sacrifice availability in that a failure of a primary node can make the database unavailable for writes.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] All distributed SQL implementations require some kind of temporal synchronization to guarantee consistency.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] With the exception of Spanner, most do not use custom hardware to provide atomic clocks.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Spanner is able to synchronize writes with temporal guarantees.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Implementations without custom hardware require servers to compare clock offsets and potentially retry reads.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] CockroachDB, YugabyteDB and others have at times referred to themselves as NewSQL databases.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Some of the NewSQL databases have fundamentally different architectures, but were cited as examples of NewSQL by Matthew Aslett who coined the term.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] In essence, distributed SQL databases are built from the ground-up and NewSQL databases include replication and sharding technologies added to existing client-server relational databases like PostgreSQL.
[src:tidb/distributed-sql] Some experts define DistributedSQL databases as a more specific subset of NewSQL databases.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] As a distributed database, TiDB is designed to consist of multiple components.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] These components communicate with each other and form a complete TiDB system.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The TiDB server is a stateless SQL layer that exposes the connection endpoint of the MySQL protocol to the outside.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The TiDB server receives SQL requests, performs SQL parsing and optimization, and ultimately generates a distributed execution plan.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] It is horizontally scalable and provides the unified interface to the outside through the load balancing components such as TiProxy, Linux Virtual Server (LVS), HAProxy, ProxySQL or F5.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] It does not store data and is only for computing and SQL analyzing, transmitting actual data read request to TiKV nodes (or TiFlash nodes).
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The PD server is the metadata managing component of the entire cluster.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] It stores metadata of real-time data distribution of every single TiKV node and the topology structure of the entire TiDB cluster, provides the TiDB Dashboard management UI, and allocates transaction IDs to distributed transactions.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The PD server is "the brain" of the entire TiDB cluster because it not only stores metadata of the cluster, but also sends data scheduling command to specific TiKV nodes according to the data distribution state reported by TiKV nodes in real time.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] In addition, the PD server consists of three nodes at least and has high availability.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] It is recommended to deploy an odd number of PD nodes.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The TiKV server is responsible for storing data.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] TiKV is a distributed transactional key-value storage engine.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] Each Region stores the data for a particular Key Range which is a left-closed and right-open interval from StartKey to EndKey.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] Multiple Regions exist in each TiKV node.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] TiKV APIs provide native support to distributed transactions at the key-value pair level and supports the Snapshot Isolation level isolation by default.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] This is the core of how TiDB supports distributed transactions at the SQL level.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] After processing SQL statements, the TiDB server converts the SQL execution plan to an actual call to the TiKV API.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] All the data in TiKV is automatically maintained in multiple replicas (three replicas by default), so TiKV has native high availability and supports automatic failover.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] The TiFlash server is a special type of storage server.
[src:tidb/tidb-architecture] Unlike ordinary TiKV nodes, TiFlash stores data by column, mainly designed to accelerate analytical processing.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Based on the distributed storage provided by TiKV, TiDB builds the computing engine that combines great capability of transactional processing with that of data analysis.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This document starts by introducing a data mapping algorithm that maps data from TiDB database tables to (Key, Value) key-value pairs in TiKV, then introduces how TiDB manages metadata, and finally illustrates the architecture of the TiDB SQL layer.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] For the storage solution on which the computing layer is dependent, this document only introduces the row-based storage structure of TiKV.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] For OLAP services, TiDB introduces a column-based storage solution TiFlash as a TiKV extension.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This section describes the scheme for mapping data to (Key, Value) key-value pairs in TiDB.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] In a relational database, a table might have many columns.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] To map the data of each column in a row to a (Key, Value) key-value pair, you need to consider how to construct the Key.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] First of all, in OLTP scenarios, there are many operations such as adding, deleting, changing, and searching for data on a single or multiple rows, which needs the database to read a row of data quickly.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Therefore, each key should have a unique ID (either explicit or implicit) to make it quick to locate.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Then, many OLAP queries require a full table scan.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] If you can encode the keys of all rows in a table into a range, the whole table can be efficiently scanned by range queries.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] `tablePrefix` and `recordPrefixSep` are both special string constants used to distinguish other data in Key space.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The exact values of the string constants are introduced in Summary of mapping relationships.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] TiDB supports both primary keys and secondary indexes (both unique and non-unique indexes).
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Similar to the table data mapping scheme, TiDB assigns an index ID to each index of the table represented by `IndexID`.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] For primary keys and unique indexes, it is needed to quickly locate the corresponding `RowID` based on the key-value pair, so such a key-value pair is encoded as follows.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] For ordinary secondary indexes that do not need to satisfy the uniqueness constraint, a single key might correspond to multiple rows.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] It needs to query corresponding `RowID` according to the range of keys.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Also note that in the above encoding schemes, no matter table data or index data key encoding scheme, all rows in a table have the same key prefix, and all data of an index also has the same prefix.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Data with the same prefixes are thus arranged together in TiKV's key space.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Therefore, by carefully designing the encoding scheme of the suffix part to ensure that the pre-encoding and post-encoding comparisons remain the same, the table data or index data can be stored in TiKV in an ordered manner.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Using this encoding scheme, all row data in a table is arranged orderly by `RowID` in the TiKV's key space, and the data of a particular index is also arranged sequentially in the key space according to the specific value of the index data (`indexedColumnsValue`).
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This section shows a simple example for you to understand the Key-Value mapping relationship of TiDB.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Suppose the following table exists in TiDB.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Suppose there are 3 rows of data in the table.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Each row of data is mapped to a (Key, Value) key-value pair, and the table has an `int` type primary key, so the value of `RowID` is the value of this primary key.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] In addition to the primary key, the table has a non-unique ordinary secondary index, `idxAge`.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The above example shows the mapping rule from a relational model to a Key-Value model in TiDB, and the consideration behind this mapping scheme.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Each database and table in TiDB has metadata that indicates its definition and various attributes.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This information also needs to be persisted, and TiDB stores this information in TiKV as well.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Each database or table is assigned a unique ID.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] As the unique identifier, when table data is encoded to Key-Value, this ID is encoded in the Key with the `m_` prefix.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This constructs a key-value pair with the serialized metadata stored in it.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] In addition, TiDB also uses a dedicated (Key, Value) key-value pair to store the latest version number of structure information of all tables.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This key-value pair is global, and its version number is increased by `1` each time the state of the DDL operation changes.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] TiDB stores this key-value pair persistently in the PD server with the key of `/tidb/ddl/global_schema_version`, and Value is the version number value of the `int64` type.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Meanwhile, because TiDB applies schema changes online, it keeps a background thread that constantly checks whether the version number of the table structure information stored in the PD server changes.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] This thread also ensures that the changes of version can be obtained within a certain period of time.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] TiDB's SQL layer, TiDB Server, translates SQL statements into Key-Value operations, forwards the operations to TiKV, the distributed Key-Value storage layer, assembles the results returned by TiKV, and finally returns the query results to the client.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] These nodes themselves do not store data and are completely equivalent.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The simplest solution to SQL computing is the mapping of table data to Key-Value as described in the previous section, which maps SQL queries to KV queries, acquires the corresponding data through the KV interface, and performs various computations.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] For example, to execute the `select count(*) from user where name = "TiDB"` SQL statement, TiDB needs to read all data in the table, then checks whether the `name` field is `TiDB`, and if so, returns this row.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Scan Key Range: read the data in TiKV according to the key range constructed above.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Filter data: for each row of data read, calculate the `name = "TiDB"` expression.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] If the result is `true`, return to this row.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Calculate `Count(*)`: for each row that meets the requirements, add up to the result of `Count(*)`.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] To solve the problems above, the computation should be as close to the storage node as possible to avoid a large number of RPC callings.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] First of all, the SQL predicate condition `name = "TiDB"` should be pushed down to the storage node for computation, so that only valid rows are returned, which avoids meaningless network transfers.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Then, the aggregation function `Count(*)` can also be pushed down to the storage nodes for pre-aggregation, and each node only has to return a result of `Count(*)`.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The SQL layer will sum up the `Count(*)` results returned by each node.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The previous sections introduce some functions of the SQL layer and I hope you have a basic understanding of how SQL statements are handled.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] In fact, TiDB's SQL layer is much more complicated, with many modules and layers.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] The user's SQL request is sent to TiDB Server either directly or via `Load Balancer`.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] TiDB Server will parse `MySQL Protocol Packet`, get the content of requests, parse the SQL request syntactically and semantically, develop and optimize query plans, execute a query plan, get and process the data.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] All data is stored in the TiKV cluster, so in this process, TiDB Server needs to interact with TiKV and get the data.
[src:tidb/tidb-computing] Finally, TiDB Server needs to return the query results to the user.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] TiDB (/'taɪdiːbi:/, "Ti" stands for Titanium) is an open-source distributed SQL database that supports Hybrid Transactional and Analytical Processing (HTAP) workloads.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] It is MySQL compatible and features horizontal scalability, strong consistency, and high availability.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] The goal of TiDB is to provide users with a one-stop database solution that covers OLTP (Online Transactional Processing), OLAP (Online Analytical Processing), and HTAP services.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] TiDB is suitable for various use cases that require high availability and strong consistency with large-scale data.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] TiDB Self-Managed is a product option of TiDB, where users or organizations can deploy and manage TiDB on their own infrastructure with complete flexibility.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] With TiDB Self-Managed, you can enjoy the power of open source, distributed SQL while retaining full control over your environment.
[src:tidb/tidb-overview] The following video introduces key features of TiDB.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] This document introduces some design ideas and key concepts of TiKV.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] The first thing to decide for a data storage system is the data storage model, that is, in what form the data is saved.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV's choice is the Key-Value model and provides an ordered traversal method.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Note that the KV storage model for TiKV described in this document has nothing to do with tables of SQL.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] This document does not discuss any concepts related to SQL and only focuses on how to implement a high-performance, high-reliability, distributed Key-Value storage such as TiKV.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] For any persistent storage engine, data is eventually saved on disk, and TiKV is no exception.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV does not write data directly on the disk, but stores data in RocksDB, which is responsible for the data storage.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] The reason is that it costs a lot to develop a standalone storage engine, especially a high-performance standalone engine that requires careful optimization.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] RocksDB is an excellent standalone storage engine open-sourced by Facebook.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] This engine can meet various requirements of TiKV for a single engine.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Here, you can simply consider RocksDB as a single persistent Key-Value Map.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] What's more, the implementation of TiKV faces a more difficult thing: to secure data safety in case a single machine fails.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] A simple way is to replicate data to multiple machines, so that even if one machine fails, the replicas on other machines are still available.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] In other words, you need a data replication scheme that is reliable, efficient, and able to handle the situation of a failed replica.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] All of these are made possible by the Raft algorithm.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] This document only briefly introduces Raft.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] For more details, you can see In Search of an Understandable Consensus Algorithm.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV use Raft to perform data replication.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Each data change will be recorded as a Raft log.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Through Raft log replication, data is safely and reliably replicated to multiple nodes of the Raft group.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] However, according to Raft protocol, successful writes only need that data is replicated to the majority of nodes.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] In summary, TiKV can quickly store data on disk via the standalone machine RocksDB, and replicate data to multiple machines via Raft in case of machine failure.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Data is written through the interface of Raft instead of to RocksDB.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] With the implementation of Raft, TiKV becomes a distributed Key-Value storage.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Even with a few machine failures, TiKV can automatically complete replicas by virtue of the native Raft protocol, which does not impact the application.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] To make it easy to understand, let's assume that all data only has one replica.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] As mentioned earlier, TiKV can be regarded as a large, orderly KV Map, so data is distributed across multiple machines in order to achieve horizontal scalability.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV chooses the second solution that divides the whole Key-Value space into a series of consecutive Key segments.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Each Region can be described by `[StartKey, EndKey)`, a left-closed and right-open interval.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] The default size limit for each Region is 256 MiB and the size can be configured.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Note that the Region here has nothing to do with the table in SQL.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] In this document, forget about SQL and focus on KV for now.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] These two tasks are very important and will be introduced one by one.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] As we distribute and replicate data in Regions, we have a distributed Key-Value system that, to some extent, has the capability of disaster recovery.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] You no longer need to worry about the capacity, or disk failure and data loss.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV supports multi-version concurrency control (MVCC).
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Consider a scenario where Client A is writing to a key simultaneously as Client B is reading the same key.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Without the MVCC mechanism, these read and write operations would be mutually exclusive, posing performance issues and deadlocks in a distributed scenario.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] However, With MVCC, as long as Client B performs a read operation at a logical time earlier than the Client A write operation, then Client B can correctly read the original value at the same time Client A performs the write operation.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Even if the key is modified multiple times by multiple write operations, Client B can still read the old value according to its logical time.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV MVCC is implemented by appending a version number to the key.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Note that for multiple versions of the same Key, versions with larger numbers are placed first (see the Key-Value section where Keys are arranged in order), so that when you obtain Value through Key + Version, the Key of MVCC can be constructed with Key and Version, which is `Key_Version`.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Then you can directly locate the first position greater than or equal to this `Key_Version` through RocksDB's `SeekPrefix(Key_Version)` API.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] Transaction of TiKV adopts the model used by Google in BigTable: Percolator.
[src:tidb/tidb-storage] TiKV's implementation is inspired by this paper, with a lot of optimizations.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB can expand both SQL processing and storage capacity by adding new nodes.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB acts like it is a MySQL 8.0 server to applications.
[src:tidb/tidb] A user can continue to use all of the existing MySQL client libraries.
[src:tidb/tidb] Because TiDB's SQL processing layer is built from scratch, it is not a MySQL fork.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB internally shards a table into small range-based chunks that are referred to as "Regions".
[src:tidb/tidb] Each Region defaults to approximately 100 MB in size, and TiDB uses a two-phase commit internally to ensure that regions are maintained in a transactionally consistent way.
[src:tidb/tidb] The storage layer of TiDB, called TiKV, became a Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) member project in August 2018, as a Sandbox level project, and became an incubation-level hosted project in May 2019.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiKV graduated from CNCF in September 2020.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB can support both online transaction processing (OLTP) and online analytical processing (OLAP) workloads.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB has two storage engines: TiKV, a rowstore, and TiFlash, a columnstore.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB uses the Raft consensus algorithm to ensure that data is available and replicated throughout storage in Raft groups.
[src:tidb/tidb] In the event of failure, a Raft group will automatically elect a new leader for the failed member, and self-heal the TiDB cluster.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB has a vector data type and vector indexes.
[src:tidb/tidb] This allows TiDB to be used as Vector database in AI Retrieval-augmented generation applications.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB can be deployed in a Kubernetes-enabled cloud environment by using TiDB Operator.
[src:tidb/tidb] An Operator is a method of packaging, deploying, and managing a Kubernetes application.
[src:tidb/tidb] It is designed for running stateful workloads and was first introduced by CoreOS in 2016.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB Operator was originally developed by PingCAP and open-sourced in August, 2018.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB Operator can be used to deploy TiDB on a laptop, Google Cloud Platform’s Google Kubernetes Engine, and Amazon Web Services’ Elastic Container Service for Kubernetes.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB 4.0 introduces TiUP, a cluster operation and maintenance tool.
[src:tidb/tidb] It helps users quickly install and configure a TiDB cluster with a few commands.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB has a series of open-source tools built around it to help with data replication and migration for existing MySQL and MariaDB users.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB Data Migration (DM) is suited for replicating data from already sharded MySQL or MariaDB tables to TiDB.
[src:tidb/tidb] A common use case of DM is to connect MySQL or MariaDB tables to TiDB, treating TiDB almost as a slave, then directly run analytical workloads on this TiDB cluster in near real-time.
[src:tidb/tidb] Backup & Restore (BR) is a distributed backup and restore tool for TiDB cluster data.
[src:tidb/tidb] Dumpling is a data export tool that exports data stored in TiDB or MySQL.
[src:tidb/tidb] It lets users make logical full backups or full dumps from TiDB or MySQL.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiDB Lightning is a tool that supports high speed full-import of a large MySQL dump into a new TiDB cluster.
[src:tidb/tidb] This tool is used to populate an initially empty TiDB cluster with much data, in order to speed up testing or production migration.
[src:tidb/tidb] The import speed improvement is achieved by parsing SQL statements into key-value pairs, then directly generate Sorted String Table (SST) files to RocksDB.
[src:tidb/tidb] TiCDC is a change data capture tool which streams data from TiDB to other systems like Apache Kafka.
